## Humans evolved to be raised by villages, not nuclear families

Sarah Blaffer Hrdy's work on cooperative breeding provides the evolutionary foundation. In *Mothers and Others* (2009), she argued humans are **cooperative breeders** — a species where alloparents (anyone other than biological parents) help rear offspring. This is unique among great apes and, Hrdy argues, preceded and drove the evolution of human prosociality, empathy, and theory of mind. Shared care generated selection pressures favoring "youngsters better at monitoring intentions, mental states and preferences of others." Her warning carries weight: if cooperative breeding structures erode, "we may lose the very trait that makes us human — the ability to empathize." Her 2024 *Father Time* extends this analysis to male nurturing capacity.

Grandparent effects are well-documented. Sear and Coall (2011) reviewed 19 studies finding grandparents beneficial to grandchild well-being in **77% of cases**. Sadruddin et al. (2019) conducted a global systematic review screening 12,699 abstracts and identifying 206 studies documenting grandparental influence through contact, caregiving, and financial support. The "grandmother hypothesis" (Hawkes et al., 1998) proposed that post-reproductive women's foraging efficiency increased grandchild survival, supported by data from African hunter-gatherers and West African horticulturalists.

Cross-cultural evidence supports the village model with important nuance. Among the Hadza of Tanzania, Crittenden and Marlowe found alloparenting includes unrelated individuals in reciprocal arrangements. Kibbutz research is particularly instructive: Sagi et al. (1985, 1994) found communal sleeping arrangements reduced secure attachment, but Aviezer, van IJzendoorn, and Sagi's 1994 *Psychological Bulletin* review of 70 years of kibbutz data showed high-quality group daytime care supported social competence comparable to family-reared children. The lesson: **communal care with maintained primary attachment bonds was beneficial; severing those bonds was not.**

The family structure debate, framed through a diversity lens, reveals that mechanisms matter more than forms. McLanahan and Sandefur's influential 1994 study found children living apart from one parent face roughly double the risk of dropping out of high school and becoming teenage parents, but the critical mechanism was "largely because of differences in economic resources and parental time — NOT inherent family form." When economic well-being is controlled, "the association between family structure and the child's economic wellbeing in adulthood disappears" (PSID longitudinal data). Paul Amato's meta-analyses found effects "moderate, not catastrophic — most children of divorce function within normal ranges." High-conflict marriages cause more harm than calm divorces. The key variables across all family structures are **stability, economic resources, relationship quality, and access to social capital** — not family configuration per se.

