## Ableism narrows the container that holds us all

The neurodiversity paradigm emerged from Judy Singer's 1998 thesis coining the term, explicitly using the metaphor: "just as biodiversity is essential for system stability, so neurodiversity may be essential for cultural stability." Nick Walker (collected in *Neuroqueer Heresies*, 2021) formalized three principles: neurodiversity is natural and valuable; there is no "normal" mind; and the social dynamics around neurological difference mirror those around other forms of diversity. Steve Silberman's *NeuroTribes* (2015) provided historical grounding, and Thomas Armstrong's work (*The Power of Neurodiversity*, 2011; *AMA Journal of Ethics*, 2015) connected neurodiversity to biodiversity and cultural diversity as parallel adaptive systems.

Critical disability studies reframe ableism as a system that constrains everyone. Fiona Kumari Campbell (*Contours of Ableism*, 2009) reconceived disability studies as "studies of ableism," defining it as "a network of beliefs, processes and practices that produces a particular kind of self and body projected as the perfect, species-typical and therefore essential and fully human." Her key insight: ableism doesn't just harm disabled people — it **produces a normative standard of abledness that constrains everyone**. Robert McRuer's "compulsory able-bodiedness" (*Crip Theory*, 2006), modeled on Adrienne Rich's compulsory heterosexuality, exposed how able-bodied identity is a fiction "everyone is expected to perform" — narrowing acceptable human embodiment for all. Rosemarie Garland-Thomson's concept of "the Normate" (1997) — the constructed identity of those who wield normative power — similarly argues this fiction constrains everyone. Douglas Baynton's foundational 2001 essay demonstrated that "disability has functioned historically to justify inequality for disabled people themselves, but it has also done so for women, for minority groups, and for immigrants."

The connection between ableism and colonialism is increasingly documented. Hutcheon and Lashewicz (2020, *Disability & Society*) traced three mechanisms by which ableist violence functions as a colonial tool. Anishinaabe scholar Nicole Ineese-Nash proposed: "Disability is contextual... Elders say that disability occurs when the expectation of the environment is not aligned with the individual's capacities or gifts." Konrad's edited volume *Disability, the Environment, and Colonialism* argues "disability is not just an unintended consequence of the colonial enterprise but the very means by which a nation-state's biopower is exercised." Erevelles (2011, *Disability and Difference in Global Contexts*) connected disability to race, colonialism, and political economy. Sunaura Taylor's *Beasts of Burden* (2017) showed ableism's devaluation of dependency harms our relationship with the entire living world.

