## The strongest objections sharpen the argument

The most important scientific counter-argument comes from Gould and Lewontin's 1979 "Spandrels" paper: not all variation is adaptive. Traits can be spandrels (architectural by-products), products of genetic drift, developmental constraints, or mutation-selection balance. Sella and Barton (2019, *Nature Reviews Genetics*) provided compelling evidence that heritable variation in human complex traits evolves under **mutation-selection-drift balance**. Latrille et al. (2024, *PLOS Genetics*) estimated **15–45% of beneficial mutations in mammals** are not truly adaptive but merely restore fitness lost to prior deleterious fixations. Williams (1966) and Dawkins (1976) argued group selection is generally weaker than individual selection, meaning claims about group-level benefits of diversity require careful justification. The honest scientific position acknowledges three categories of variation: maintained by selection, tolerated by selection, and existing despite selection. The thesis works best when it argues the first category is **larger than deficit models assume**, not that it encompasses all variation.

The strongest ethical critique comes from disability justice. Sins Invalid's framework grounds inclusion in **inherent worth** — "people have inherent worth outside of commodity relations and capitalist notions of productivity" — not in adaptive utility. Mia Mingus argues for interdependence grounded in relational care and dignity, explicitly challenging the myth of independence as itself a form of cultural narrowing. Sunaura Taylor warns that maintaining ability as "the metric that determines value" ensures some will always be marginalized, regardless of how generously "ability" is defined. Fiona Kumari Campbell argues that requiring disability to prove its worth — even through sophisticated evolutionary arguments — is a form of ableism that still positions able-bodiedness as the norm against which disability must justify itself. The **conditional-versus-unconditional inclusion distinction** is critical: "We should include because diversity is adaptive" makes inclusion contingent on demonstrated usefulness, while "No body or mind can be left behind" makes it a matter of justice.

Critiques of the neurodiversity paradigm center on **high-support-needs representation**. The movement has been "largely shaped by verbally communicative adults with strong self-reflection and advocacy abilities" (Dwyer, 2022). Jonathan Mitchell and other autistic critics argue many advocates "cannot speak for" those who cannot articulate their own position. Nirmala Erevelles challenges disability studies' investment in "a powerful, resistant, and rational voice" that systematically excludes cognitive difference. Damian Milton's "double empathy problem" (2012, *Disability & Society*) — that social communication difficulties are bidirectional, not unilateral autistic deficits — has gained substantial empirical support (Crompton et al., 2020; Sasson et al., 2017) but needs extension to address those with significant intellectual impairments.

